Note: Graph Queries
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Reading node count via the list length keeps the count consistent with the
nodes list itself - no separate counter to drift. Schedulers and statistics
pass the count to bound array sizes and progress prints.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null graph. Loads the nodes List at offset 8 and returns
List.length.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) - one load plus one list-length read.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_node_count" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let count be List.length(nodes)
    Return count
End Process

@Reasoning:
Edge count is read from the edges-list length for the same drift-free reason
as get_node_count. Verification and statistics consume this value.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null graph. Loads the edges List at offset 16 and returns
List.length.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_edge_count" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let count be List.length(edges)
    Return count
End Process

@Reasoning:
Linear-scan membership is acceptable here because validation passes use this
sparingly and the more common "by-id" lookup goes through node_id_map (O(1)).
Looking up by raw pointer is the cheap option when callers already have the
node pointer in hand.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards graph and node. Loads the nodes List, walks each entry with a
while loop, and returns true as soon as a pointer match is found. Returns
false after the full scan.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(N) linear scan where N is node count. Avoid in inner loops - prefer
get_node(id) when the id is available.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "has_node" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let n be List.get(nodes, i)
        If n is equal to node:
            Return true
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Mirror of has_node - linear by-pointer scan for edges. Used by validation
passes that already have the edge pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards graph and edge. Loads the edges List, walks it with a while loop,
returning true on the first match and false after exhausting the list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(E) linear scan. Use get_edge(id) for O(1) lookups when id is available.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "has_edge" that takes graph as Integer, edge as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If edge is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let edge_count be List.length(edges)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than edge_count:
        Let e be List.get(edges, i)
        If e is equal to edge:
            Return true
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
ID-keyed access is the fast path during translation - the builder hands out
ids and later passes resolve back to node pointers via the node_id_map kept
in lockstep by add_node and remove_node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null graph. Reads node_id_map at offset 40, tests Dict.has_key,
and returns Dict.get on hit; returns 0 on miss.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) hashed lookup. Hot accessor for value-map resolution.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. Returned pointer is borrowed from the node-storage of the graph.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_node" that takes graph as Integer, node_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let node_id_map be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 40)
    If Dict.has_key(node_id_map, node_id):
        Let node be Dict.get(node_id_map, node_id)
        Return node
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric counterpart to get_node. Edge id is used by passes that record
dependencies by id (e.g. metadata side-tables) instead of pointer.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns 0 for null graph. Reads edge_id_map at offset 48, tests Dict.has_key,
returns Dict.get on hit; returns 0 on miss.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) hashed lookup.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_edge" that takes graph as Integer, edge_id as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let edge_id_map be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 48)
    If Dict.has_key(edge_id_map, edge_id):
        Let edge be Dict.get(edge_id_map, edge_id)
        Return edge
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
The node_inputs adjacency dict gives O(1) "what edges feed this node?"
queries for def-use walks. Returning a fresh empty list for missing entries
lets callers use a uniform List interface without branching on null.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns a fresh empty list for null graph or null node. Reads node_inputs at
offset 24, tests for the node key, returns the stored list on hit; otherwise
returns a freshly constructed empty list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) hashed lookup. Empty-list construction is the only non-trivial cost on
the miss path - callers that test count first via List.length amortise it.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Returned list on hit is BORROWED - mutating it directly will affect the
graph's adjacency state. Callers must use this only for read iteration.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_node_inputs" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let node_inputs be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 24)
    If Dict.has_key(node_inputs, node):
        Let inputs be Dict.get(node_inputs, node)
        Return inputs
    End If

    Return List.create()
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric to get_node_inputs - O(1) "what edges leave this node?" needed by
forward-walks (use-def, dominator trees) and by add_edge's symmetric update.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns a fresh empty list for null graph or null node. Reads node_outputs at
offset 32, tests for the node key, returns the stored list on hit; returns a
fresh empty list otherwise.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) hashed lookup.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Returned list on hit is BORROWED; read-only iteration only.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_node_outputs" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let node_outputs be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 32)
    If Dict.has_key(node_outputs, node):
        Let outputs be Dict.get(node_outputs, node)
        Return outputs
    End If

    Return List.create()
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returning the unique-predecessor node set (not edge set) is what schedulers
and dominance computations want. De-duplicating inline is cheaper than
returning duplicates and asking callers to filter, and the typical fan-in is
small enough that the inner linear search stays cheap.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns a fresh empty list for null graph or null node. Iterates the
node_inputs adjacency list via get_node_inputs; for each edge, fetches
get_edge_source and, if non-null, runs an inner linear scan over the
predecessors list to skip duplicates before appending.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(D^2) where D is the in-degree, because of the inner de-duplication scan.
Acceptable since the typical in-degree is small (1..4). Replace with a Set
when in-degree grows.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Returns a FRESH list owned by the caller. Pointer entries are borrowed and
point into the graph's node storage.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_node_predecessors" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let predecessors be List.create()
    Let incoming_edges be get_node_inputs(graph, node)
    Let edge_count be List.length(incoming_edges)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be List.get(incoming_edges, i)
        Let source be get_edge_source(edge)
        If source is not equal to 0:
            Note: Check if already in list to avoid duplicates
            Let already_added be false
            Let pred_count be List.length(predecessors)
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than pred_count:
                Let pred be List.get(predecessors, j)
                If pred is equal to source:
                    Set already_added to true
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
            If already_added is equal to false:
                List.append(predecessors, source)
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return predecessors
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric to get_node_predecessors. Returns the unique successor node set
for use by forward-traversal (BFS, DFS, topological sort, dominance).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns a fresh empty list for null graph or null node. Walks the outgoing
edge list from get_node_outputs, fetches get_edge_dest for each, and uses an
inner linear scan to suppress duplicates before appending.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(D^2) on out-degree D. Same trade-off as get_node_predecessors.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Returns a FRESH list owned by the caller; pointer entries are borrowed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_node_successors" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let successors be List.create()
    Let outgoing_edges be get_node_outputs(graph, node)
    Let edge_count be List.length(outgoing_edges)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be List.get(outgoing_edges, i)
        Let dest be get_edge_dest(edge)
        If dest is not equal to 0:
            Note: Check if already in list to avoid duplicates
            Let already_added be false
            Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than succ_count:
                Let succ be List.get(successors, j)
                If succ is equal to dest:
                    Set already_added to true
                End If
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
            If already_added is equal to false:
                List.append(successors, dest)
            End If
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return successors
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Graph Traversal Algorithms
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Kahn's algorithm is the right choice for Bifrost because we want an
execution-order list (useful for scheduling) AND a cycle detector in the same
pass. Bifrost graphs are required to be DAGs - returning an empty list on
cycle gives downstream passes a single "valid DAG?" check (compare lengths)
without needing a separate has_cycle invocation.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an empty list on null graph. Builds an in_degree Dict by counting
each node's incoming edges via get_node_inputs. Initialises a queue with all
zero-in-degree nodes. Repeatedly dequeues a node u, appends it to the sorted
result, walks u's successors (via get_node_successors), decrements their
in-degree counters, and enqueues any that reach zero. After the queue
drains, compares the result length to the node count: equal means the sort
succeeded, otherwise a cycle exists and an empty list is returned.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E). Space O(V) for the in_degree dict and queue. List.remove_at(queue, 0)
is O(|queue|) - if profiling shows it dominates, swap to a true queue.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read on graph state plus auxiliary allocations (in_degree dict, queue,
result list). All allocations are freed when the caller releases the result.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "topological_sort" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Note: Get all nodes from graph
    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    Note: Compute in-degree for each node
    Let in_degree be Dict.create()
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let incoming be get_node_inputs(graph, node)
        Let degree be List.length(incoming)
        Dict.set(in_degree, node, degree)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Initialize queue with all nodes that have in-degree 0
    Let queue be List.create()
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than node_count:
        Set node to List.get(nodes, j)
        Set degree to Dict.get(in_degree, node)
        If degree is equal to 0:
            List.append(queue, node)
        End If
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Process nodes in topological order
    Let sorted be List.create()
    While List.length(queue) is greater than 0:
        Note: Dequeue first node
        Let u be List.get(queue, 0)
        List.remove_at(queue, 0)
        List.append(sorted, u)

        Note: Decrease in-degree of successors
        Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, u)
        Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than succ_count:
            Let v be List.get(successors, k)
            Let v_degree be Dict.get(in_degree, v)
            Let new_degree be v_degree minus 1
            Dict.set(in_degree, v, new_degree)

            Note: If in-degree becomes 0, add to queue
            If new_degree is equal to 0:
                List.append(queue, v)
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Note: Check if all nodes were sorted (no cycle)
    Let sorted_count be List.length(sorted)
    If sorted_count is equal to node_count:
        Return sorted
    End If

    Note: Graph has cycle - return empty list
    Return List.create()
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reverse topological order is needed for some backward analyses (live-out,
reverse dataflow). Composing on top of topological_sort keeps the cycle-
detection contract identical so callers only need one error path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list on null graph. Runs topological_sort and walks the result
back-to-front, appending each entry into a new reversed list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) for the underlying sort plus O(V) for the reverse walk. One extra
allocation for the reversed list - replace with in-place reverse if profiling
demands.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read of the forward topological sort. Returned list is freshly owned.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "reverse_topological_sort" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let forward_sorted be topological_sort(graph)
    Let sorted_count be List.length(forward_sorted)

    Note: Reverse the list
    Let reversed be List.create()
    Let i be sorted_count minus 1
    While i is greater than or equal to 0:
        Let node be List.get(forward_sorted, i)
        List.append(reversed, node)
        Set i to i minus 1
    End While

    Return reversed
End Process

@Reasoning:
Preorder DFS visits nodes before their subgraphs, so it is the right
traversal for tasks that want to act on a node first (e.g. labelling,
collecting source-line metadata before descending into a subtree). The
recursion is bounded by graph depth - Bifrost graphs are typically shallow
relative to their breadth so the recursion stack stays small.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list on null graph or null start_node. Allocates a visited Set
and result List, then calls dfs_preorder_helper to perform the actual walk.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E). Stack depth equals the longest path from start_node. Visited Set
prevents re-traversal of reconvergent paths.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; allocations are visited Set and result List. Both freed at caller
discretion.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dfs_preorder" that takes graph as Integer, start_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If start_node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let visited be Set.create()
    Let result be List.create()

    Note: Call recursive DFS helper
    dfs_preorder_helper(graph, start_node, visited, result)

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
The helper splits recursion from the top-level dfs_preorder so the caller
need not own the visited set and result list. Storing visited in a Set
guarantees O(1) hit testing while the result List preserves traversal order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Adds node to the visited Set, appends to result (preorder visit), fetches
get_node_successors, walks each successor and recurses for unvisited ones.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(degree) per call; total O(V+E) across the recursion. Recursion depth equals
longest path length.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates the caller-owned visited Set and result List; both are passed in by
reference. No external state.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dfs_preorder_helper" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    node as Integer,
    visited as Integer,
    result as Integer
    returns Nothing:

    Note: Mark node as visited
    Set.add(visited, node)

    Note: Add node to result (PREORDER - visit before children)
    List.append(result, node)

    Note: Visit all unvisited successors
    Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, node)
    Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than succ_count:
        Let succ be List.get(successors, i)
        If Set.contains(visited, succ) is equal to false:
            dfs_preorder_helper(graph, succ, visited, result)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Postorder DFS visits children first, then parent - ideal for accumulating
results bottom-up (height computation, reverse-postorder schedules, SSA
phi insertion). Reversing a postorder gives a valid topological order, which
is occasionally cheaper than running Kahn for ad-hoc scheduling.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list on null inputs. Allocates a visited Set and a result List,
then calls dfs_postorder_helper to walk the subgraph rooted at start_node.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) with recursion depth equal to longest path. Same trade-offs as
dfs_preorder.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dfs_postorder" that takes graph as Integer, start_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If start_node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let visited be Set.create()
    Let result be List.create()

    Note: Call recursive DFS helper
    dfs_postorder_helper(graph, start_node, visited, result)

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Symmetric to dfs_preorder_helper but appends after recursing - that single
re-ordering is the difference between pre- and post-order.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Marks node visited, fetches successors, recurses for each unvisited
successor, and appends the node to result after all children have been
processed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(degree) per call.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates caller-owned visited Set and result List.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "dfs_postorder_helper" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    node as Integer,
    visited as Integer,
    result as Integer
    returns Nothing:

    Note: Mark node as visited
    Set.add(visited, node)

    Note: Visit all unvisited successors
    Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, node)
    Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than succ_count:
        Let succ be List.get(successors, i)
        If Set.contains(visited, succ) is equal to false:
            dfs_postorder_helper(graph, succ, visited, result)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add node to result (POSTORDER - visit after children)
    List.append(result, node)
End Process

@Reasoning:
BFS gives shortest-distance ordering from start - useful for level-aware
optimisation (e.g. when fusion needs to operate within a depth window). It
also avoids the stack-depth concerns of DFS for very deep graphs.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list on null inputs. Allocates a visited Set, result List, and
queue List. Seeds the queue with start_node and marks it visited. In the main
loop, dequeues from index 0, appends to result, fetches successors, and
enqueues each unvisited successor while marking it visited.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) time and space. List.remove_at(queue, 0) is O(|queue|); for large
graphs replace with a circular buffer if profiling demands.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; three allocations (visited, result, queue). All freed at caller
discretion.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "bfs" that takes graph as Integer, start_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If start_node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let visited be Set.create()
    Let result be List.create()
    Let queue be List.create()

    Note: Initialize with start node
    Set.add(visited, start_node)
    List.append(queue, start_node)

    Note: Process nodes in breadth-first order
    While List.length(queue) is greater than 0:
        Note: Dequeue first node
        Let u be List.get(queue, 0)
        List.remove_at(queue, 0)
        List.append(result, u)

        Note: Enqueue all unvisited successors
        Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, u)
        Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than succ_count:
            Let v be List.get(successors, i)
            If Set.contains(visited, v) is equal to false:
                Set.add(visited, v)
                List.append(queue, v)
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Return result
End Process

@Reasoning:
Root nodes (no predecessors) are entry-points for topological sort and for
traversal that starts from inputs. Returning them as a list lets schedulers
process multiple disjoint subgraphs in parallel.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an empty list for null graph. Walks the nodes List and tests each
node's incoming-edge count via get_node_inputs + List.length; if zero,
appends to the roots list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V) - one length check per node. The List.length on each adjacency entry is
O(1) so the overall cost stays linear.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. Result list is freshly owned by caller; entries are borrowed.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "find_roots" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)
    Let roots be List.create()

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let incoming be get_node_inputs(graph, node)
        Let in_count be List.length(incoming)
        If in_count is equal to 0:
            List.append(roots, node)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return roots
End Process

@Reasoning:
Leaf nodes (no successors) are graph sinks - Output nodes and side-effect
operations that have no further consumers. Schedulers use the leaf set as
the start point for reverse-topological traversal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an empty list for null graph. Walks the nodes List and tests each
node's outgoing-edge count via get_node_outputs + List.length; if zero,
appends to the leaves list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. Result list freshly owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "find_leaves" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)
    Let leaves be List.create()

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let outgoing be get_node_outputs(graph, node)
        Let out_count be List.length(outgoing)
        If out_count is equal to 0:
            List.append(leaves, node)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return leaves
End Process

@Reasoning:
Reachability from a node is the basis for dead-code elimination (anything
unreachable from inputs can be deleted) and for subgraph isolation. Reusing
dfs_preorder keeps semantics aligned with the preorder traversal.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list on null inputs. Delegates to dfs_preorder which performs
the DFS walk and returns the reachable-node list directly.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) via dfs_preorder. No extra allocation beyond what dfs_preorder needs.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_reachable_nodes" that takes graph as Integer, start_node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If start_node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Note: Use DFS preorder to collect all reachable nodes
    Let reachable be dfs_preorder(graph, start_node)
    Return reachable
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Graph Validation Algorithms
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Bifrost requires DAG inputs (cycles would let schedulers deadlock and would
break SSA def-use chains). Piggybacking on topological_sort gives the
DAG-or-not answer in one O(V+E) pass instead of running has_cycle separately.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false for null graph. Runs topological_sort and compares the result
length to get_node_count - if they match every node was scheduled, so the
graph is acyclic.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) via topological_sort. Cheaper than running has_cycle separately when
the caller has not already computed a sort.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. The intermediate sort list is dropped immediately after the
length comparison.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "is_dag" that takes graph as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let sorted be topological_sort(graph)
    Let sorted_count be List.length(sorted)
    Let total_nodes be get_node_count(graph)

    If sorted_count is equal to total_nodes:
        Return true
    End If

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Three-colour DFS is the canonical O(V+E) cycle detector that handles
disconnected components by restarting at every White node. Returning early
on the first cycle keeps the cost low when the graph is corrupt.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false for null graph. Reads the nodes list, builds a color Dict
initialised to 0 (White) for every node, then iterates the nodes list - for
each still-White node it invokes has_cycle_dfs and returns true on the first
cycle found. Returns false after exhausting all nodes.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E). Recursion depth equals longest DFS path; tail-friendly for shallow
Bifrost DAGs.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read on graph state; allocates a color Dict that is freed when this
routine returns.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "has_cycle" that takes graph as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    Note: Initialize color map (0=White, 1=Gray, 2=Black)
    Let color be Dict.create()
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Dict.set(color, node, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check each component for cycles
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than node_count:
        Set node to List.get(nodes, j)
        Let node_color be Dict.get(color, node)
        If node_color is equal to 0:
            Let cycle_found be has_cycle_dfs(graph, node, color)
            If cycle_found is equal to true:
                Return true
            End If
        End If
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
The Gray-equals-on-current-path invariant is the only signal three-colour DFS
needs to detect cycles: an edge to a Gray node is a back-edge by definition.
Recursive structure mirrors the colour state machine.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Marks the input node Gray (1). Walks each successor, reads the successor's
colour from the Dict; Gray returns true immediately (cycle found); White
recurses and propagates true on any nested cycle. After the successor loop
the node is marked Black (2) and false is returned.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(degree) per call; total O(V+E) across recursion.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates the caller-owned color Dict.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "has_cycle_dfs" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    node as Integer,
    color as Integer
    returns Boolean:

    Note: Mark node as Gray (currently visiting)
    Dict.set(color, node, 1)

    Note: Check all successors
    Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, node)
    Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than succ_count:
        Let succ be List.get(successors, i)
        Let succ_color be Dict.get(color, succ)

        Note: Gray successor means back edge (cycle detected)
        If succ_color is equal to 1:
            Return true
        End If

        Note: White successor needs recursive check
        If succ_color is equal to 0:
            Let cycle_found be has_cycle_dfs(graph, succ, color)
            If cycle_found is equal to true:
                Return true
            End If
        End If

        Note: Black successor already processed (no cycle)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Mark node as Black (finished visiting)
    Dict.set(color, node, 2)

    Return false
End Process

@Reasoning:
Returning the offending cycle (not just a Boolean) is what error messages
need: the verifier dumps the cycle path so the user can see exactly which
nodes form the loop. Builds a parent Dict alongside the color Dict so the
DFS helper can reconstruct the path on detection.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list for null graph. Reads the nodes list; initialises color
and parent Dicts (each node mapped to 0). Walks the nodes list - for each
White node, invokes find_cycle_dfs, returning its result if non-empty.
Returns an empty list when no cycle is found.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) worst case. The parent Dict adds O(V) memory over has_cycle but no
extra time beyond the DFS itself.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read on graph state; allocates color and parent Dicts plus the cycle
result list. Result list owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "find_cycle" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    Note: Initialize color map and parent map for path reconstruction
    Let color be Dict.create()
    Let parent be Dict.create()
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Dict.set(color, node, 0)
        Dict.set(parent, node, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Check each component for cycles
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than node_count:
        Set node to List.get(nodes, j)
        Let node_color be Dict.get(color, node)
        If node_color is equal to 0:
            Let cycle_path be find_cycle_dfs(graph, node, color, parent)
            Let cycle_len be List.length(cycle_path)
            If cycle_len is greater than 0:
                Return cycle_path
            End If
        End If
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return List.create()
End Process

@Reasoning:
On back-edge detection, walking the parent chain from the current node back
to the Gray ancestor gives a concrete cycle path that can be printed for
diagnostics. Parent pointers are recorded as the DFS descends so the chain
is always available.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Marks the node Gray. Walks successors; before each step records the parent
pointer (succ -> node). When a Gray successor is seen, builds a cycle list
by walking parent links from the current node until reaching the Gray
ancestor and returns it. White successors recurse; non-empty returns
propagate upward. Marks the node Black before returning an empty list when
no cycle was found.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(degree) per call; path reconstruction is O(cycle_length).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates caller-owned color and parent Dicts; allocates the cycle list on
detection.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "find_cycle_dfs" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    node as Integer,
    color as Integer,
    parent as Integer
    returns Integer:

    Note: Mark node as Gray
    Dict.set(color, node, 1)

    Note: Check all successors
    Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, node)
    Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than succ_count:
        Let succ be List.get(successors, i)
        Let succ_color be Dict.get(color, succ)

        Note: Record parent for path reconstruction
        Dict.set(parent, succ, node)

        Note: Gray successor means back edge - reconstruct cycle
        If succ_color is equal to 1:
            Let cycle be List.create()
            Let current be node
            While current is not equal to 0:
                List.append(cycle, current)
                If current is equal to succ:
                    Return cycle
                End If
                Set current to Dict.get(parent, current)
            End While
        End If

        Note: White successor needs recursive check
        If succ_color is equal to 0:
            Let cycle_path be find_cycle_dfs(graph, succ, color, parent)
            Let cycle_len be List.length(cycle_path)
            If cycle_len is greater than 0:
                Return cycle_path
            End If
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Mark node as Black
    Dict.set(color, node, 2)

    Return List.create()
End Process

@Reasoning:
The validator is the gatekeeper before backends consume the graph. The
checks are ordered to fail fast: cycles are the cheapest and most catastrophic
failure, then dangling endpoints, then type consistency (the most expensive
per-edge check). Returning false on any single failure prevents broken graphs
from reaching codegen.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false for null graph. Runs is_dag; on failure returns false.
Walks the edges list (offset 16), reads source and dest from each edge via
get_edge_source / get_edge_dest, returns false if either is null or if has_node
rejects the endpoint. Finally runs validate_types and returns its result.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) for is_dag plus O(E times V) worst case for the per-edge has_node scan
(E edges, each calling O(V) linear node lookup). For large graphs this could
be O(V+E) by
keying off node_id_map - acceptable for current graph sizes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. False return MUST abort lowering - feeding an invalid graph to
codegen produces wrong code or crashes.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_graph" that takes graph as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check graph is acyclic
    Let is_acyclic be is_dag(graph)
    If is_acyclic is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Validate all edges have valid endpoints
    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let edge_count be List.length(edges)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be List.get(edges, i)
        Let source be get_edge_source(edge)
        Let dest be get_edge_dest(edge)

        If source is equal to 0:
            Return false
        End If
        If dest is equal to 0:
            Return false
        End If

        Let source_exists be has_node(graph, source)
        Let dest_exists be has_node(graph, dest)

        If source_exists is equal to false:
            Return false
        End If
        If dest_exists is equal to false:
            Return false
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate type compatibility on all edges
    Let types_valid be validate_types(graph)
    If types_valid is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Type consistency between an edge's data_type tag and its source node's output
type is the type-system invariant that codegen relies on - emitting the wrong
SIMD width or float vs. int would silently produce wrong results. One linear
sweep is enough since every edge can be checked independently.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false for null graph. Walks the edges list (offset 16), and for each
edge: reads its data type, the source pointer, the source's output type, and
runs types_compatible. Returns false on the first mismatch.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(E) - one compatibility check per edge. types_compatible is constant-time
for primitive types and linear in tensor rank for shaped types.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. False return is a hard rejection - downstream lowering must abort.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_types" that takes graph as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let edge_count be List.length(edges)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be List.get(edges, i)
        Let edge_type be get_edge_data_type(edge)
        Let source be get_edge_source(edge)
        Let source_type be get_node_output_type(source)

        Note: Check type compatibility
        Let compatible be types_compatible(edge_type, source_type)
        If compatible is equal to false:
            Return false
        End If

        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Per-node validation supports incremental verification during graph rewrites -
a pass that adds or modifies a single node can re-verify just the affected
node and its incident edges instead of running the full validate_graph pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false for null inputs. Confirms the node is registered via has_node,
then reads get_node_output_type and returns false if it is null. Walks the
input edges (get_node_inputs) and output edges (get_node_outputs) and
validates each via validate_edge; returns false on any rejection.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(degree(node)) for incident-edge validation plus the cost of the inner
validate_edge calls. Cheap for incremental checks.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read. False return signals the node violates a graph invariant; callers
must not use the node further until the issue is repaired.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_node" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check node exists in graph
    Let exists be has_node(graph, node)
    If exists is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check node has valid output type
    Let node_type be get_node_output_type(node)
    If node_type is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Validate all input edges
    Let inputs be get_node_inputs(graph, node)
    Let in_count be List.length(inputs)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than in_count:
        Let edge be List.get(inputs, i)
        Let edge_valid be validate_edge(graph, edge)
        If edge_valid is equal to false:
            Return false
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Validate all output edges
    Let outputs be get_node_outputs(graph, node)
    Let out_count be List.length(outputs)
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than out_count:
        Set edge to List.get(outputs, j)
        Set edge_valid to validate_edge(graph, edge)
        If edge_valid is equal to false:
            Return false
        End If
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return true
End Process

@Reasoning:
Edge validation enforces the four invariants every edge must hold: edge is
registered, both endpoints are non-null and registered, and the payload
type matches the producer's output type.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns false on null inputs. Calls has_edge to confirm registration, reads
source and dest via get_edge_source / get_edge_dest, returns false if either
is null. Calls has_node on each endpoint, returns false on either rejection.
Reads the edge's data_type and source's output_type, runs types_compatible,
and returns false on mismatch.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V) worst case due to has_node's linear scan. Acceptable for ad-hoc
verification.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "validate_edge" that takes graph as Integer, edge as Integer returns Boolean:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If edge is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check edge exists in graph
    Let exists be has_edge(graph, edge)
    If exists is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Get source and destination nodes
    Let source be get_edge_source(edge)
    Let dest be get_edge_dest(edge)

    If source is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If
    If dest is equal to 0:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check source and dest exist in graph
    Let source_exists be has_node(graph, source)
    Let dest_exists be has_node(graph, dest)

    If source_exists is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If
    If dest_exists is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Note: Check type compatibility
    Let edge_type be get_edge_data_type(edge)
    Let source_type be get_node_output_type(source)
    Let compatible be types_compatible(edge_type, source_type)
    If compatible is equal to false:
        Return false
    End If

    Return true
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Graph Analysis Algorithms
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Node depth (max distance from any root) is the foundation for level-aware
scheduling and for prioritising fusion candidates that share the same depth.
Computing it once via DP on the topological order is far cheaper than
re-deriving depth from each root with separate BFS calls.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty Dict for null graph. Runs topological_sort; returns empty Dict
on cycle (sort returns empty). Initialises a depths Dict with all nodes mapped
to 0. Walks the sorted order: for each node, fetches predecessors, takes the
maximum predecessor depth, and writes node depth = max+1 (or 0 if the node has
no predecessors). Returns the populated depths Dict.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) time, O(V) space. Each predecessor is visited exactly once.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read on graph state; returned Dict owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_depths" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Note: Get topological order for processing
    Let sorted be topological_sort(graph)
    Let sorted_count be List.length(sorted)
    If sorted_count is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Note: Initialize depths to 0
    Let depths be Dict.create()
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than sorted_count:
        Let node be List.get(sorted, i)
        Dict.set(depths, node, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute depths in topological order
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than sorted_count:
        Set node to List.get(sorted, j)
        Let predecessors be get_node_predecessors(graph, node)
        Let pred_count be List.length(predecessors)

        Note: Find maximum predecessor depth
        Let max_depth be 0
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than pred_count:
            Let pred be List.get(predecessors, k)
            Let pred_depth be Dict.get(depths, pred)
            If pred_depth is greater than max_depth:
                Set max_depth to pred_depth
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While

        Note: Node depth is max predecessor depth + 1
        Let node_depth be max_depth plus 1
        If pred_count is equal to 0:
            Set node_depth to 0
        End If
        Dict.set(depths, node, node_depth)

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return depths
End Process

@Reasoning:
Node height (max distance to any leaf) is the symmetric counterpart of depth.
It is needed by backward-flow analyses and to estimate latency from a node to
the graph's outputs. Reverse-topological DP yields it in one pass.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty Dict for null graph. Runs reverse_topological_sort; returns empty
Dict on cycle. Initialises heights to 0 for every node, then walks the reverse
order computing height = max(successor heights) + 1 (or 0 for leaves with no
successors).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) time, O(V) space.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_heights" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Note: Get reverse topological order (leaves first)
    Let sorted be reverse_topological_sort(graph)
    Let sorted_count be List.length(sorted)
    If sorted_count is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Note: Initialize heights to 0
    Let heights be Dict.create()
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than sorted_count:
        Let node be List.get(sorted, i)
        Dict.set(heights, node, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute heights in reverse topological order
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than sorted_count:
        Set node to List.get(sorted, j)
        Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, node)
        Let succ_count be List.length(successors)

        Note: Find maximum successor height
        Let max_height be 0
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than succ_count:
            Let succ be List.get(successors, k)
            Let succ_height be Dict.get(heights, succ)
            If succ_height is greater than max_height:
                Set max_height to succ_height
            End If
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While

        Note: Node height is max successor height + 1
        Let node_height be max_height plus 1
        If succ_count is equal to 0:
            Set node_height to 0
        End If
        Dict.set(heights, node, node_height)

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return heights
End Process

@Reasoning:
The critical path is the longest chain of dependencies through the graph - the
schedule lower bound. Identifying it lets the scheduler prioritise nodes on
that path to minimise overall latency, and lets fusion passes avoid breaking
the path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list for null graph. Topo-sorts; returns empty on cycle.
Initialises distance and parent Dicts. Walks the topological order: for each
node u, for each successor v, if distance(u)+1 > distance(v), updates
distance(v) and sets parent(v)=u (weight=1 today; weighted edges can be added
later). After DP, scans for the max-distance node and backtracks parent
pointers to reconstruct the path, then reverses to root-to-leaf order.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) for the DP plus O(V) for max-search plus O(|path|) for the
reconstruction. Total O(V+E). Two Dict allocations.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; result list owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "find_critical_path" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Note: Get topological order for DP processing
    Let sorted be topological_sort(graph)
    Let sorted_count be List.length(sorted)
    If sorted_count is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Note: Initialize distance and parent for DP
    Let distance be Dict.create()
    Let parent be Dict.create()
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than sorted_count:
        Let node be List.get(sorted, i)
        Dict.set(distance, node, 0)
        Dict.set(parent, node, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute longest paths using DP
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than sorted_count:
        Let u be List.get(sorted, j)
        Let u_dist be Dict.get(distance, u)
        Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, u)
        Let succ_count be List.length(successors)

        Let k be 0
        While k is less than succ_count:
            Let v be List.get(successors, k)
            Let v_dist be Dict.get(distance, v)

            Note: Weight is 1 for unweighted graph (can be extended)
            Let weight be 1
            Let new_dist be u_dist plus weight

            Note: Update if longer path found
            If new_dist is greater than v_dist:
                Dict.set(distance, v, new_dist)
                Dict.set(parent, v, u)
            End If

            Set k to k plus 1
        End While

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Find node with maximum distance (end of critical path)
    Let max_dist be 0
    Let max_node be 0
    Let m be 0
    While m is less than sorted_count:
        Set node to List.get(sorted, m)
        Let node_dist be Dict.get(distance, node)
        If node_dist is greater than max_dist:
            Set max_dist to node_dist
            Set max_node to node
        End If
        Set m to m plus 1
    End While

    Note: Reconstruct critical path by backtracking
    Let path be List.create()
    Let current be max_node
    While current is not equal to 0:
        List.append(path, current)
        Set current to Dict.get(parent, current)
    End While

    Note: Reverse path to get root→leaf order
    Let path_len be List.length(path)
    Let reversed_path be List.create()
    Let n be path_len minus 1
    While n is greater than or equal to 0:
        Set node to List.get(path, n)
        List.append(reversed_path, node)
        Set n to n minus 1
    End While

    Return reversed_path
End Process

@Implementation:
Computes the dominator tree for the graph using Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy algorithm.
Node d dominates node n if every path from entry to n must go through d.

Algorithm (Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy):
1. Initialize: entry dominates only itself, all others dominated by all nodes
2. Iterate until convergence:
   - For each node n (except entry):
     - new_dom(n) = {n} ∪ (∩ dom(p) for all predecessors p of n)
   - If new_dom(n) ≠ dom(n), update and mark changed
3. Build immediate dominator map from dominator sets

Time Complexity: O(V * E) worst case, typically converges in 2-3 iterations
Space Complexity: O(V^2) for dominator sets

Memory Safety:
- Returns empty dictionary for null graph
- Handles graphs with no entry node
@End Implementation

@Reasoning:
Dominators are used by code motion (you can hoist a node above its dominator
without changing semantics) and by control-equivalence reasoning in fusion.
The iterative Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy formulation is correct for non-reducible
graphs and converges quickly on Bifrost DAGs.
@End Reasoning

@Performance_Hints:
O(V*E) worst case in the iterative loop; typical convergence is 2-3 iterations
for DAGs. Memory is O(V^2) for full dominator sets. Replace with the
near-linear Lengauer-Tarjan algorithm if graphs exceed a few thousand nodes.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read on graph; returned Dict and embedded Lists are owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_dominators" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    If node_count is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Note: Find entry node (node with no predecessors)
    Let entry_node be 0
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let preds be get_node_predecessors(graph, node)
        If List.length(preds) is equal to 0:
            Set entry_node to node
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    If entry_node is equal to 0:
        Note: No entry node found, use first node
        Set entry_node to List.get(nodes, 0)
    End If

    Note: Initialize dominator sets
    Let dominators be Dict.create()

    Note: Entry node dominates only itself
    Let entry_doms be List.create()
    List.append(entry_doms, entry_node)
    Dict.set(dominators, entry_node, entry_doms)

    Note: All other nodes initially dominated by all nodes
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Set node to List.get(nodes, i)
        If node is not equal to entry_node:
            Let all_nodes be List.create()
            Let j be 0
            While j is less than node_count:
                List.append(all_nodes, List.get(nodes, j))
                Set j to j plus 1
            End While
            Dict.set(dominators, node, all_nodes)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Iterate until convergence (Cooper-Harvey-Kennedy)
    Let changed be true
    While changed is equal to true:
        Set changed to false

        Set i to 0
        While i is less than node_count:
            Set node to List.get(nodes, i)

            If node is not equal to entry_node:
                Note: new_dom(n) = {n} ∪ (∩ dom(p) for all preds p)
                Let predecessors be get_node_predecessors(graph, node)
                Let pred_count be List.length(predecessors)

                If pred_count is greater than 0:
                    Note: Start with first predecessor's dominators
                    Let first_pred be List.get(predecessors, 0)
                    Let intersection be List.copy(Dict.get(dominators, first_pred))

                    Note: Intersect with remaining predecessors' dominators
                    Let p be 1
                    While p is less than pred_count:
                        Let pred be List.get(predecessors, p)
                        Let pred_doms be Dict.get(dominators, pred)
                        Set intersection to set_intersection(intersection, pred_doms)
                        Set p to p plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Add node itself
                    Let new_doms be List.create()
                    List.append(new_doms, node)
                    Set j to 0
                    While j is less than List.length(intersection):
                        List.append(new_doms, List.get(intersection, j))
                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Check if changed
                    Let old_doms be Dict.get(dominators, node)
                    Let sets_equal be set_equal(old_doms, new_doms)
                    If sets_equal is equal to false:
                        Dict.set(dominators, node, new_doms)
                        Set changed to true
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Return dominators
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bifrost graphs are DAGs in normal operation, but during in-progress rewrites a
fusion pass can temporarily introduce cycles - SCC detection lets the verifier
spot and refuse the broken graph. Tarjan's single-pass algorithm reports SCCs
in reverse-topological order which is convenient for the verifier's reporting.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list for null graph. Allocates sccs list, traversal stack, and
three Dicts (index_map, lowlink_map, on_stack_map) plus current_index counter.
Walks the nodes list, invoking tarjan_strongconnect on every unindexed node;
the helper pushes/pops the stack and emits SCCs into the sccs list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) - single DFS pass. Stack and three Dicts each O(V) space.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; SCC result list owned by caller, each SCC sublist owned by the
outer list.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "find_strongly_connected_components" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    Note: Tarjan's algorithm state
    Let sccs be List.create()
    Let stack be List.create()
    Let index_map be Dict.create()
    Let lowlink_map be Dict.create()
    Let on_stack_map be Dict.create()
    Let current_index be 0

    Note: Run Tarjan DFS for each unvisited node
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let has_index be Dict.has_key(index_map, node)
        If has_index is equal to false:
            Set current_index to tarjan_strongconnect(
                graph, node, sccs, stack,
                index_map, lowlink_map, on_stack_map, current_index
            )
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return sccs
End Process

@Reasoning:
The recursive worker keeps the index/lowlink/on-stack state explicit so the
outer driver can resume after a recursion completes. Lowlink minimisation on
back-edges is the heart of Tarjan's correctness argument.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Sets index_map(node)=current_index and lowlink_map(node)=current_index, then
increments current_index. Pushes node onto stack and marks it on_stack. Walks
each successor: if unindexed, recurses then updates lowlink_map(node) with
min(self, succ.lowlink); if indexed and on_stack, updates lowlink_map(node)
with min(self, succ.index). After walking, if lowlink == index the node is an
SCC root - pops the stack until node reappears, creates an SCC list, and
appends it to sccs. Returns the updated current_index.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
Amortised O(degree) per call; total O(V+E) across the full Tarjan run. Each
edge is examined once, each node is pushed/popped once.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates caller-owned sccs list, stack, and three Dicts. No external state.
@End Security_Scope

Note: Helper process for Tarjan's algorithm recursive DFS
Process called "tarjan_strongconnect" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    node as Integer,
    sccs as Integer,
    stack as Integer,
    index_map as Integer,
    lowlink_map as Integer,
    on_stack_map as Integer,
    current_index as Integer
    returns Integer:

    Note: Set index and lowlink for this node
    Dict.set(index_map, node, current_index)
    Dict.set(lowlink_map, node, current_index)
    Let current_index be current_index plus 1

    Note: Push node onto stack
    List.append(stack, node)
    Dict.set(on_stack_map, node, true)

    Note: Visit all successors
    Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, node)
    Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
    Let s be 0
    While s is less than succ_count:
        Let successor be List.get(successors, s)
        Let has_index be Dict.has_key(index_map, successor)

        If has_index is equal to false:
            Note: Successor not visited, recurse
            Set current_index to tarjan_strongconnect(
                graph, successor, sccs, stack,
                index_map, lowlink_map, on_stack_map, current_index
            )

            Note: Update lowlink: lowlink[node] = min(lowlink[node], lowlink[successor])
            Let node_lowlink be Dict.get(lowlink_map, node)
            Let succ_lowlink be Dict.get(lowlink_map, successor)
            If succ_lowlink is less than node_lowlink:
                Dict.set(lowlink_map, node, succ_lowlink)
            End If
        Otherwise:
            Note: Successor already visited, check if on stack
            Let succ_on_stack be Dict.get(on_stack_map, successor)
            If succ_on_stack is equal to true:
                Note: Successor is on stack, update lowlink[node] = min(lowlink[node], index[successor])
                Set node_lowlink to Dict.get(lowlink_map, node)
                Let succ_index be Dict.get(index_map, successor)
                If succ_index is less than node_lowlink:
                    Dict.set(lowlink_map, node, succ_index)
                End If
            End If
        End If

        Set s to s plus 1
    End While

    Note: If node is SCC root, pop stack to form SCC
    Let node_index be Dict.get(index_map, node)
    Set node_lowlink to Dict.get(lowlink_map, node)

    If node_lowlink is equal to node_index:
        Note: Node is SCC root, pop until we reach node
        Let scc be List.create()
        Let popped_node be 0

        Note: Pop stack until we reach current node
        While popped_node is not equal to node:
            Let stack_len be List.length(stack)
            Set popped_node to List.get(stack, stack_len minus 1)
            List.remove_at(stack, stack_len minus 1)
            Dict.set(on_stack_map, popped_node, false)
            List.append(scc, popped_node)
        End While

        Note: Add this SCC to results
        List.append(sccs, scc)
    End If

    Return current_index
End Process

@Reasoning:
Transitive closure pre-computes "can node u reach node v?" for every pair so
later queries (e.g. for fusion legality "do these two share a dependency
ancestor?") are O(1) lookups instead of fresh DFS runs. Memory is quadratic
so callers should free it promptly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty Dict for null graph. Walks every node and stores its
get_reachable_nodes result under the node key in the closure Dict.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V*(V+E)) time, O(V^2) space. Reuse across passes amortises the cost; for
giant graphs prefer per-query DFS.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; closure Dict and the embedded reachable lists are owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "compute_transitive_closure" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Let closure be Dict.create()
    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    Note: For each node, compute reachable nodes
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let reachable be get_reachable_nodes(graph, node)
        Dict.set(closure, node, reachable)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Return closure
End Process

@Reasoning:
Subgraph extraction is the foundation of kernel-extraction passes: pick a
region of the graph (typically the body of a recognised matmul or conv) and
clone it into its own BifrostGraph so a backend can lower that region as a
single kernel.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns a fresh empty graph for null inputs. Allocates a new graph via
create_graph. Walks the original nodes list; if a node is in node_set, calls
add_node on the subgraph. Walks the edges list; only adds an edge when both
its source and dest are in node_set (cross-boundary edges are dropped).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) where V and E are original graph sizes. Set.contains is O(1) for a
hashed set; with a list-backed set this becomes O(V*V_set).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Reads original graph; allocates a fresh subgraph owned by caller. Original
node and edge pointers are SHARED between the two graphs - removing from one
must not free the other's references.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "get_subgraph" that takes graph as Integer, node_set as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return create_graph()
    End If
    If node_set is equal to 0:
        Return create_graph()
    End If

    Note: Create new graph for subgraph
    Let subgraph be create_graph()

    Note: Add all nodes in node_set to subgraph
    Let node_count be Set.size(node_set)
    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let total_nodes be List.length(nodes)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than total_nodes:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        If Set.contains(node_set, node) is equal to true:
            add_node(subgraph, node)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add edges where both endpoints are in node_set
    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let edge_count be List.length(edges)
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be List.get(edges, j)
        Let source be get_edge_source(edge)
        Let dest be get_edge_dest(edge)

        Let source_in_set be Set.contains(node_set, source)
        Let dest_in_set be Set.contains(node_set, dest)

        If source_in_set is equal to true:
            If dest_in_set is equal to true:
                add_edge(subgraph, edge)
            End If
        End If

        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return subgraph
End Process

@Reasoning:
Graph merging is used when several subgraphs (one per MIR basic block) need
to be combined into a single function-level graph for cross-block fusion.
Null-tolerant inputs let callers pass partial collections without branching.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates a fresh merged graph via create_graph. If graph1 is non-null, walks
its nodes and edges lists, calling add_node and add_edge for each. Same for
graph2. Returns the merged graph.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V1+V2+E1+E2) - each item is added once. Two passes (one per input) keep
the implementation simple at the cost of one extra loop.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Node and edge pointers are SHARED with the inputs. Callers must not free
either input graph while the merged graph is in use, or the merged graph will
contain dangling pointers.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "merge_graphs" that takes graph1 as Integer, graph2 as Integer returns Integer:
    Let merged be create_graph()

    Note: Add all nodes and edges from graph1
    If graph1 is not equal to 0:
        Let nodes1 be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph1, 8)
        Let node_count1 be List.length(nodes1)
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than node_count1:
            Let node be List.get(nodes1, i)
            add_node(merged, node)
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Let edges1 be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph1, 16)
        Let edge_count1 be List.length(edges1)
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than edge_count1:
            Let edge be List.get(edges1, j)
            add_edge(merged, edge)
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Add all nodes and edges from graph2
    If graph2 is not equal to 0:
        Let nodes2 be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph2, 8)
        Let node_count2 be List.length(nodes2)
        Let k be 0
        While k is less than node_count2:
            Set node to List.get(nodes2, k)
            add_node(merged, node)
            Set k to k plus 1
        End While

        Let edges2 be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph2, 16)
        Let edge_count2 be List.length(edges2)
        Let m be 0
        While m is less than edge_count2:
            Set edge to List.get(edges2, m)
            add_edge(merged, edge)
            Set m to m plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Return merged
End Process

@Reasoning:
Deep cloning is essential when a pass needs to experiment with rewrites
without committing them (compare cost before and after fusion). The
old-to-new node map is critical: cloned edges must point at cloned nodes,
not at the originals, otherwise the graph would be a hybrid.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns a fresh empty graph for null input. Allocates the cloned graph and a
node_map Dict. Walks the original nodes: calls clone_node for each, adds the
clone to the cloned graph, and records old->new in node_map. Walks original
edges: looks up new_source / new_dest via node_map, reads kind and data_type
from the old edge, calls create_edge with new endpoints, copies metadata via
set_edge_metadata, and adds via add_edge.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) plus the per-node clone cost. One Dict allocation for node_map.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Allocates fresh node and edge structs owned by the cloned graph; cloned graph
and originals share no pointers. Metadata Dict pointers are SHARED on copy -
caller must not mutate metadata via either graph if it could affect the
other.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "clone_graph" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return create_graph()
    End If

    Note: Create new graph
    Let cloned be create_graph()

    Note: Clone all nodes and build mapping
    Let node_map be Dict.create()
    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let old_node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let new_node be clone_node(old_node)
        add_node(cloned, new_node)
        Dict.set(node_map, old_node, new_node)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Clone all edges with updated node references
    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let edge_count be List.length(edges)
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than edge_count:
        Let old_edge be List.get(edges, j)

        Note: Get old source and dest
        Let old_source be get_edge_source(old_edge)
        Let old_dest be get_edge_dest(old_edge)

        Note: Map to new source and dest
        Let new_source be Dict.get(node_map, old_source)
        Let new_dest be Dict.get(node_map, old_dest)

        Note: Create new edge with updated references
        Let edge_kind be get_edge_kind(old_edge)
        Let edge_type be get_edge_data_type(old_edge)
        Let new_edge be create_edge(j plus 1, new_source, new_dest, edge_kind, edge_type)

        Note: Copy metadata if present
        Let metadata be get_edge_metadata(old_edge)
        If metadata is not equal to 0:
            set_edge_metadata(new_edge, metadata)
        End If

        add_edge(cloned, new_edge)
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Return cloned
End Process

@Reasoning:
Aggregating common graph metrics into a single Dict avoids forcing every
caller (verifier, pass-pipeline log, diagnostics output) to re-derive the
same numbers. Keys are stable strings so consumers can pull what they need
without coordinating on ordering.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty Dict for null graph. Allocates the stats Dict. Computes
node_count and edge_count via the get_*_count helpers, root_count and
leaf_count via find_roots / find_leaves, then walks the nodes list scanning
compute_depths and compute_heights to find max_depth and max_height. Records
avg_degree as edge_count/node_count when node_count>0. Calls is_dag and
stores 1/0. All values are inserted via Dict.set with string keys.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) dominated by compute_depths and compute_heights (each is V+E). Multiple
Dict allocations for the intermediate maps. Not in hot loops - only called by
verifier and diagnostic code.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read on graph; returned stats Dict owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "graph_statistics" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return Dict.create()
    End If

    Let stats be Dict.create()

    Note: Node and edge counts
    Let node_count be get_node_count(graph)
    Let edge_count be get_edge_count(graph)
    Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("node_count"), node_count)
    Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("edge_count"), edge_count)

    Note: Root and leaf counts
    Let roots be find_roots(graph)
    Let root_count be List.length(roots)
    Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("root_count"), root_count)

    Let leaves be find_leaves(graph)
    Let leaf_count be List.length(leaves)
    Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("leaf_count"), leaf_count)

    Note: Depth and height analysis
    Let depths be compute_depths(graph)
    Let heights be compute_heights(graph)

    Let max_depth be 0
    Let max_height be 0
    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let node_depth be Dict.get(depths, node)
        Let node_height be Dict.get(heights, node)
        If node_depth is greater than max_depth:
            Set max_depth to node_depth
        End If
        If node_height is greater than max_height:
            Set max_height to node_height
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("max_depth"), max_depth)
    Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("max_height"), max_height)

    Note: Average degrees
    If node_count is greater than 0:
        Let avg_degree be edge_count divided by node_count
        Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("avg_degree"), avg_degree)
    End If

    Note: Check if DAG
    Let is_acyclic be is_dag(graph)
    Let acyclic_val be 0
    If is_acyclic is equal to true:
        Set acyclic_val to 1
    End If
    Dict.set(stats, String.from_string("is_dag"), acyclic_val)

    Return stats
End Process

Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
Note: Graph Transformation and Optimization
Note: ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════

@Reasoning:
Dead-code elimination shrinks the graph before downstream analyses run -
unreachable nodes consume memory and dilute statistics, and may confuse
verifiers. The reachable-from-any-root criterion is safe because legitimate
Bifrost computation always flows from Input/Constant roots.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns immediately for null graph. Calls find_roots and runs
get_reachable_nodes from each root, unioning the results into a reachable
Set. Walks the nodes list collecting every node NOT in reachable into a
to_remove list, then walks to_remove calling remove_node on each (deferring
removal avoids invalidating the iteration cursor on the nodes list).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) for the reachability sweep plus O(D*N) for remove_node calls where D
is the dead-node count and N is the total node count (remove_node's id-map
cleanup is linear). For typical graphs D is small so the total cost stays
near O(V+E).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates the graph in place. Dead-node memory is not freed - only the graph's
references are cleared; reclamation happens at graph teardown.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "eliminate_dead_nodes" that takes graph as Integer returns Nothing:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Note: Find all reachable nodes from roots
    Let roots be find_roots(graph)
    Let root_count be List.length(roots)
    Let reachable be Set.create()

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than root_count:
        Let root be List.get(roots, i)
        Let reachable_from_root be get_reachable_nodes(graph, root)
        Let reach_count be List.length(reachable_from_root)
        Let j be 0
        While j is less than reach_count:
            Let node be List.get(reachable_from_root, j)
            Set.add(reachable, node)
            Set j to j plus 1
        End While
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Remove all unreachable nodes
    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)
    Let to_remove be List.create()

    Let k be 0
    While k is less than node_count:
        Set node to List.get(nodes, k)
        If Set.contains(reachable, node) is equal to false:
            List.append(to_remove, node)
        End If
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While

    Note: Remove collected dead nodes
    Let remove_count be List.length(to_remove)
    Let m be 0
    While m is less than remove_count:
        Set node to List.get(to_remove, m)
        remove_node(graph, node)
        Set m to m plus 1
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Subgraph inlining is the lowering step for calls that the call-graph analysis
decided to expand: the callee's BifrostGraph replaces the call node, with
edges re-targeted so the original predecessors/successors connect to the
subgraph's roots/leaves.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Null-guards graph, target_node, and subgraph. Finds subgraph roots and
leaves. Retargets each of target_node's input edges to the first subgraph
root via set_edge_dest, and each of target_node's output edges from the first
subgraph leaf via set_edge_source. Walks the subgraph's nodes and edges
lists, calling add_node and add_edge to absorb them into the main graph.
Finally calls remove_node on the target.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V_sub + E_sub + degree(target)) - linear in subgraph size plus the target's
edge count.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates the main graph in place. The subgraph's nodes and edges become owned
by the main graph (their pointers are now reachable from the main graph's
collections); callers must not free the subgraph after inlining.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "inline_subgraph" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    target_node as Integer,
    subgraph as Integer
    returns Nothing:

    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If target_node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If
    If subgraph is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Note: Get subgraph inputs and outputs
    Let sub_roots be find_roots(subgraph)
    Let sub_leaves be find_leaves(subgraph)

    Note: Redirect target's inputs to subgraph inputs
    Let target_inputs be get_node_inputs(graph, target_node)
    Let input_count be List.length(target_inputs)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than input_count:
        Let input_edge be List.get(target_inputs, i)
        If List.length(sub_roots) is greater than 0:
            Let new_dest be List.get(sub_roots, 0)
            set_edge_dest(input_edge, new_dest)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Redirect target's outputs to subgraph outputs
    Let target_outputs be get_node_outputs(graph, target_node)
    Let output_count be List.length(target_outputs)
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than output_count:
        Let output_edge be List.get(target_outputs, j)
        If List.length(sub_leaves) is greater than 0:
            Let new_source be List.get(sub_leaves, 0)
            set_edge_source(output_edge, new_source)
        End If
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add all subgraph nodes to main graph
    Let sub_nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(subgraph, 8)
    Let sub_node_count be List.length(sub_nodes)
    Let k be 0
    While k is less than sub_node_count:
        Let sub_node be List.get(sub_nodes, k)
        add_node(graph, sub_node)
        Set k to k plus 1
    End While

    Note: Add all subgraph edges to main graph
    Let sub_edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(subgraph, 16)
    Let sub_edge_count be List.length(sub_edges)
    Let m be 0
    While m is less than sub_edge_count:
        Let sub_edge be List.get(sub_edges, m)
        add_edge(graph, sub_edge)
        Set m to m plus 1
    End While

    Note: Remove target node
    remove_node(graph, target_node)
End Process

@Reasoning:
Node fusion is the most important Bifrost optimisation - it collapses
element-wise producer/consumer pairs into a single composite kernel,
eliminating intermediate buffer materialisation and cutting memory bandwidth.
The legality checks (both are Operation discriminant 3, op-pair is in the
fusible whitelist, and they are connected by an edge) prevent fusing across
unrelated ops or non-element-wise ops.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Triple null-guards graph, node1, node2. Reads discriminants from each node
(offset 0) and returns 0 if either is not 3 (Operation). Reads op kinds from
offset 8. Calls check_operations_fusible and check_edge_exists; returns 0 on
either rejection. Reads node1's output_type (offset 24), parallelism (32),
and metadata (40) for inheritance. Merges the two input lists via
merge_input_lists. Allocates a 48-byte composite node, writes discriminant=3,
op=op1, the merged inputs, and the inherited type/parallelism/metadata.
Redirects incoming edges via redirect_incoming_edges(node1->composite) and
outgoing via redirect_outgoing_edges(node2->composite). Adds the composite
to the graph and removes node1 and node2.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(degree(node1) + degree(node2)) for the edge redirection plus the cost of
remove_node for the two originals. Hot path in the fusion optimisation pass;
the early null/discriminant/fusibility checks short-circuit quickly when the
candidate is not fusible.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Mutates the graph: allocates a new composite node, redirects edges, removes
two nodes. The metadata pointer is COPIED (shared) from node1 to the
composite - if node1's metadata Dict is freed, the composite would dangle.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "fuse_nodes" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    node1 as Integer,
    node2 as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If node1 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If
    If node2 is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Read node discriminants to verify both are Operation nodes
    Let node1_disc be Layout.memory_get_int64(node1, 0)
    Let node2_disc be Layout.memory_get_int64(node2, 0)

    Note: BifrostNode discriminants: Constant=0, Input=1, Output=2, Operation=3
    If node1_disc is not equal to 3:
        Return 0
    End If
    If node2_disc is not equal to 3:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Extract operation kinds from Operation nodes
    Note: Operation layout: discriminant(0), op(8), inputs(16), output_type(24), parallelism(32), metadata(40)
    Let op1 be Layout.memory_get_int64(node1, 8)
    Let op2 be Layout.memory_get_int64(node2, 8)

    Note: Check if operations are fusible
    Let is_fusible be check_operations_fusible(op1, op2)
    If is_fusible is equal to false:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Verify producer-consumer relationship
    Let node2_inputs be Layout.memory_get_int64(node2, 16)
    Let has_edge be check_edge_exists(graph, node1, node2)
    If has_edge is equal to false:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create composite operation node
    Note: For element-wise fusion, composite inherits parallelism from node1
    Let node1_type be Layout.memory_get_int64(node1, 24)
    Let node1_parallelism be Layout.memory_get_int64(node1, 32)
    Let node1_metadata be Layout.memory_get_int64(node1, 40)

    Note: Merge inputs: node1's inputs + node2's inputs excluding node1 output
    Let composite_inputs be merge_input_lists(
        Layout.memory_get_int64(node1, 16),
        Layout.memory_get_int64(node2, 16),
        node1
    )

    Note: Allocate composite node
    Let composite be Layout.memory_allocate(48)
    Layout.memory_set_int64(composite, 0, 3)
    Layout.memory_set_int64(composite, 8, op1)
    Layout.memory_set_int64(composite, 16, composite_inputs)
    Layout.memory_set_int64(composite, 24, node1_type)
    Layout.memory_set_int64(composite, 32, node1_parallelism)
    Layout.memory_set_int64(composite, 40, node1_metadata)

    Note: Redirect edges from node1's predecessors to composite
    redirect_incoming_edges(graph, node1, composite)

    Note: Redirect edges from node2's successors to composite
    redirect_outgoing_edges(graph, node2, composite)

    Note: Add composite to graph
    add_node(graph, composite)

    Note: Remove original nodes
    remove_node(graph, node1)
    remove_node(graph, node2)

    Return composite
End Process

@Reasoning:
Node splitting is the inverse of fusion - a complex composite operation
(BatchNorm, FullyConnected) gets decomposed into primitive nodes so that
backends without library-level support for the composite can still emit
correct code via the primitives. The pass is selective so primitive ops like
Add stay atomic.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns an empty list on null inputs. Reads the node discriminant; if not 3
(Operation), returns a singleton list containing the original node. Reads
the op_kind from offset 8 and calls check_operation_decomposable; if false,
returns the original as a singleton. Otherwise dispatches by op_kind: for
FullyConnected (kind 42) emits a MatrixMultiply (kind 15) + Add (kind 0)
pair, threading the matmul output into the add's input list; for BatchNorm
(kind 38) emits Subtract(1), Divide(3), Multiply(2), Add(0) - one per
algorithmic step. Each new node is appended to the decomposed list which is
returned.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k * degree(node)) where k is the decomposition factor (typically 2-4).
Each new node is a fresh allocation; k+1 List allocations for the per-stage
input lists and the result.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Allocates fresh nodes that the caller is expected to wire into the graph;
this routine returns the new nodes but does NOT add them to the graph or
redirect edges - that is the caller's responsibility.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "split_node" that takes graph as Integer, node as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If node is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Note: Read node discriminant
    Let node_disc be Layout.memory_get_int64(node, 0)

    Note: Only decompose Operation nodes
    If node_disc is not equal to 3:
        Let result be List.create()
        List.append(result, node)
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Read operation kind
    Let op_kind be Layout.memory_get_int64(node, 8)

    Note: Decompose based on operation type
    Note: FullyConnected (op_kind ~= 42): MatrixMultiply + Add
    Note: BatchNorm (op_kind ~= 38): (x - mean) / sqrt(variance + epsilon) * gamma + beta
    Note: LayerNorm (op_kind ~= 39): Similar to BatchNorm

    Note: Check if operation is decomposable
    Let is_decomposable be check_operation_decomposable(op_kind)

    If is_decomposable is equal to false:
        Note: Return original node for non-decomposable ops
        Set result to List.create()
        List.append(result, node)
        Return result
    End If

    Note: Perform decomposition based on operation
    Let decomposed be List.create()

    Note: FullyConnected decomposition: y = Wx + b
    If op_kind is equal to 42:
        Note: Extract inputs: weights (W), input (x), bias (b)
        Let inputs be Layout.memory_get_int64(node, 16)
        Let output_type be Layout.memory_get_int64(node, 24)

        Note: Create MatrixMultiply node: Wx
        Let matmul_node be create_operation_node(
            15, inputs, output_type
        )
        List.append(decomposed, matmul_node)

        Note: Create Add node: (Wx) + b
        Let matmul_output_list be List.create()
        List.append(matmul_output_list, matmul_node)
        Let add_node be create_operation_node(
            0, matmul_output_list, output_type
        )
        List.append(decomposed, add_node)

        Return decomposed
    End If

    Note: BatchNorm decomposition: ((x - mean) / sqrt(var + eps)) * gamma + beta
    If op_kind is equal to 38:
        Set inputs to Layout.memory_get_int64(node, 16)
        Set output_type to Layout.memory_get_int64(node, 24)

        Note: Create Subtract node: x - mean
        Let sub_node be create_operation_node(1, inputs, output_type)
        List.append(decomposed, sub_node)

        Note: Create Divide node: (x - mean) / sqrt(var + eps)
        Let sub_output be List.create()
        List.append(sub_output, sub_node)
        Let div_node be create_operation_node(3, sub_output, output_type)
        List.append(decomposed, div_node)

        Note: Create Multiply node: normalized * gamma
        Let div_output be List.create()
        List.append(div_output, div_node)
        Let mul_node be create_operation_node(2, div_output, output_type)
        List.append(decomposed, mul_node)

        Note: Create Add node: (normalized * gamma) + beta
        Let mul_output be List.create()
        List.append(mul_output, mul_node)
        Set add_node to create_operation_node(0, mul_output, output_type)
        List.append(decomposed, add_node)

        Return decomposed
    End If

    Note: For other operations, return original node
    List.append(decomposed, node)
    Return decomposed
End Process

@Reasoning:
Bifrost's scheduler can produce many valid topological orderings; choosing
one that maximises cache locality (consumers right after producers, repeated
producers staying hot) reduces memory traffic dramatically on CPU and
GPU-with-cache targets. The hot-window heuristic (last CACHE_WINDOW_SIZE
nodes) is a simple LRU proxy that costs O(1) per check.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list on null/empty graph. Phase 1: builds an in_degree Dict by
counting predecessors. Phase 2: initialises the ready_queue with all
zero-in-degree nodes. Phase 3 (greedy scheduling): while the queue is
non-empty, calls select_best_node_for_locality (which scores candidates
against the hot_nodes window of CACHE_WINDOW_SIZE=8 recently scheduled
nodes), appends the chosen node to scheduled and to hot_nodes, evicts the
oldest hot entry if the window overflows, removes the node from the
ready_queue, and decrements in-degrees of its successors, enqueuing any that
reach zero. Returns the scheduled list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V * (W + degree)) where W is the cache window size (8) and degree is the
average successor count - effectively O(V+E) since W is a small constant.
select_best_node_for_locality dominates per-iteration cost.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read on graph; returned schedule List owned by caller.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "reorder_for_locality" that takes graph as Integer returns Integer:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    If node_count is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Note: Phase 1: Compute in-degrees for topological scheduling
    Let in_degree be Dict.create()
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let preds be get_node_predecessors(graph, node)
        Dict.set(in_degree, node, List.length(preds))
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Phase 2: Initialize ready queue with nodes having in-degree 0
    Let ready_queue be List.create()
    Set i to 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Set node to List.get(nodes, i)
        Let degree be Dict.get(in_degree, node)
        If degree is equal to 0:
            List.append(ready_queue, node)
        End If
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Phase 3: Greedy cache-aware scheduling
    Let scheduled be List.create()
    Let hot_nodes be List.create()
    Constant CACHE_WINDOW_SIZE as Integer is 8

    While List.length(ready_queue) is greater than 0:
        Note: Select next node using cache locality heuristic
        Let best_node be select_best_node_for_locality(
            ready_queue, hot_nodes, graph
        )

        Note: Schedule this node
        List.append(scheduled, best_node)

        Note: Update hot nodes (cache window)
        List.append(hot_nodes, best_node)
        If List.length(hot_nodes) is greater than CACHE_WINDOW_SIZE:
            List.remove_at(hot_nodes, 0)
        End If

        Note: Remove from ready queue
        let_remove_from_list(ready_queue, best_node)

        Note: Update successors and add newly ready nodes
        Let successors be get_node_successors(graph, best_node)
        Let succ_count be List.length(successors)
        Let s be 0
        While s is less than succ_count:
            Let succ be List.get(successors, s)
            Let succ_degree be Dict.get(in_degree, succ)
            Set succ_degree to succ_degree minus 1
            Dict.set(in_degree, succ, succ_degree)

            If succ_degree is equal to 0:
                List.append(ready_queue, succ)
            End If

            Set s to s plus 1
        End While
    End While

    Return scheduled
End Process

@Reasoning:
Multi-device execution requires splitting a graph across k accelerators while
minimising cross-device data transfer (edge cuts) and balancing load. The
greedy approach with a 10x weighting on edge cuts vs load imbalance favours
communication minimisation over perfect load balance - the right trade-off
when interconnect bandwidth is the bottleneck.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns empty list on null graph or num_partitions <= 0. Allocates a
partitions list, partition_loads list, and node_to_partition Dict. Creates k
empty subgraphs and initialises load counters to 0. Topo-sorts the input.
For each node in topo order, scans each candidate partition computing
(edge_cut_cost * 10 + load_imbalance) where load_imbalance is
|current_load - avg_load|; selects the partition with the minimum total
cost, assigns the node, and bumps the load counter. After all nodes are
placed, walks the edges list and adds each edge to its source's partition;
cross-partition edges therefore remain in the source partition (callers can
detect them by comparing endpoint partitions).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V * k + E). k iterations per node make the assignment loop dominant when
k is large; for k > 8 consider clustering nodes by predecessor partition
before the scan.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Reads input graph; allocates k subgraphs (each via create_graph) and a
node_to_partition Dict. Nodes and edges are SHARED between the input graph
and the per-partition subgraphs - removing from any partition leaves the
others' references intact but the input graph still owns the underlying
storage.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "partition_graph" that takes
    graph as Integer,
    num_partitions as Integer
    returns Integer:

    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If
    If num_partitions is less than or equal to 0:
        Return List.create()
    End If

    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let node_count be List.length(nodes)

    If node_count is equal to 0:
        Let empty_partitions be List.create()
        Return empty_partitions
    End If

    Note: Perform topological sort to respect dependencies
    Let sorted_nodes be topological_sort(graph)

    Note: Initialize partitions and load tracking
    Let partitions be List.create()
    Let partition_loads be List.create()
    Let node_to_partition be Dict.create()

    Let i be 0
    While i is less than num_partitions:
        Let subgraph be create_graph()
        List.append(partitions, subgraph)
        List.append(partition_loads, 0)
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: Greedy assignment: for each node, choose partition with min cost
    Let n be 0
    While n is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(sorted_nodes, n)

        Note: Compute cost for each partition
        Let best_partition be 0
        Let min_cost be 999999999

        Let p be 0
        While p is less than num_partitions:
            Note: Cost = edge_cut_cost + load_imbalance_penalty
            Let edge_cut_cost be compute_edge_cut_cost(
                graph, node, p, node_to_partition
            )

            Let current_load be List.get(partition_loads, p)
            Let avg_load be node_count divided by num_partitions
            Let load_imbalance be current_load minus avg_load
            If load_imbalance is less than 0:
                Set load_imbalance to -load_imbalance
            End If

            Note: Total cost with weights (edge cuts more important)
            Let total_cost be (edge_cut_cost multiplied by 10) plus load_imbalance

            If total_cost is less than min_cost:
                Set min_cost to total_cost
                Set best_partition to p
            End If

            Set p to p plus 1
        End While

        Note: Assign node to best partition
        Dict.set(node_to_partition, node, best_partition)
        Let partition be List.get(partitions, best_partition)
        add_node(partition, node)

        Note: Update partition load
        Let load be List.get(partition_loads, best_partition)
        Set load to load plus 1
        List.set(partition_loads, best_partition, load)

        Set n to n plus 1
    End While

    Note: Distribute edges based on node assignments
    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let edge_count be List.length(edges)
    Let e be 0
    While e is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be List.get(edges, e)
        Let source be get_edge_source(edge)
        Let dest be get_edge_dest(edge)

        Let src_partition_idx be Dict.get(node_to_partition, source)
        Let dst_partition_idx be Dict.get(node_to_partition, dest)

        Note: Add edge to source partition (may be cross-partition edge)
        Let src_partition be List.get(partitions, src_partition_idx)
        add_edge(src_partition, edge)

        Set e to e plus 1
    End While

    Return partitions
End Process

@Reasoning:
A full string dump of a Bifrost graph is the canonical diagnostic artefact
for verifier failures and pass-pipeline traces. Including node and edge
counts in the header lets log scrapers extract size metrics without
re-parsing the body.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Returns "[NULL GRAPH]" for null graph. Builds the header string with
"BifrostGraph {" then "  Nodes: <n>" and "  Edges: <m>" via String.concatenate
of String.from_int(get_node_count) / get_edge_count. Walks the nodes list
appending each node's description, then walks the edges list appending each
edge's description (using edge_to_string).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(V+E) string concatenations; each concatenation is O(L) in the cumulative
length so the overall cost is O((V+E)^2) in the worst case. Restrict to
diagnostic paths; do not call in hot loops.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Pure read; output contains node and edge pointer values (hex-formatted via
the inner edge_to_string). Do not forward to untrusted sinks - pointer
disclosure could aid attackers.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "graph_to_string" that takes graph as Integer returns String:
    If graph is equal to 0:
        Return "[NULL GRAPH]"
    End If

    Let result be "BifrostGraph {\n"

    Note: Add statistics
    Let node_count be get_node_count(graph)
    Let edge_count be get_edge_count(graph)

    Set result to String.concatenate(result, "  Nodes: ")
    Set result to String.concatenate(result, String.from_int(node_count))
    Set result to String.concatenate(result, "\n  Edges: ")
    Set result to String.concatenate(result, String.from_int(edge_count))
    Set result to String.concatenate(result, "\n")

    Note: List all nodes
    Set result to String.concatenate(result, "  Nodes:\n")
    Let nodes be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 8)
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than node_count:
        Let node be List.get(nodes, i)
        Let node_str be node_to_string(node)
        Set result to String.concatenate(result, "    ")
        Set result to String.concatenate(result, node_str)
        Set result to String.concatenate(result, "\n")
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While

    Note: List all edges
    Set result to String.concatenate(result, "  Edges:\n")
    Let edges be Layout.memory_get_int64(graph, 16)
    Let j be 0
    While j is less than edge_count:
        Let edge be List.get(edges, j)
        Let edge_str be edge_to_string(edge)
        Set result to String.concatenate(result, "    ")
        Set result to String.concatenate(result, edge_str)
        Set result to String.concatenate(result, "\n")
        Set j to j plus 1
    End While

    Set result to String.concatenate(result, "}")
    Return result
End Process

